Trump and Economics
New York—The financial market has finally woken up, realizing Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured this globally most powerful figure's unbridled tweets and public remarks for as long as two years, and the obvious question is, what has maintained this for such a long time?
On one hand, until now, investors have been giving Trump the benefit of the doubt, only hitting him with lightning but not letting it rain.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies beneficial to corporate departments and shareholders, they will assume him to be innocent.
Many people believe that at the end of the day, "adults in the room" will restrain Trump and ensure that government policies are within bounds.
Such an assumption was largely proved in Trump's first year in office, during which the economy grew and corporate profit expectations rose — thanks to the impending tax cuts and deregulation — leading to a stellar stock market performance.
The US stock index rose by over 20% in 2017.
However, the situation took a sharp turn for the worse in 2018, especially in the last few months.
Despite corporate profits increasing by over 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the US stock market fluctuated for most of the year and then plummeted.
Currently, all indices are located in the correction interval (i.e., the most recent high has fallen by 10%) , the technology stock index (such as Nasdaq), has fallen into a bear market (a decline of 20% or more).
Despite the increasing volatility of the financial market, which reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the beginning of this year, Trump implemented a reckless tax cut, resulting in a surge in long-term interest rates, making the economy, which was already close to full employment, reach a climax.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target value of 2% led to the first wave of risk aversion in 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important US trade partners.
The market's concern about the government's protectionist policy has fluctuated throughout the year, but has now reached a new peak.
Recent US actions against China appear to be preparing a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may bring about a stagflation effect (growth weakening, inflation increasing).
After all, Trump plans to limit foreign direct investment inflows and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of labor supply in the face of increasingly serious labor shortages and skill mismatch problems.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has not yet proposed plans to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy through infrastructure projects.
Trump continually criticizes the hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors of enterprises in Twitter and other contexts, especially in the tech sector, which is already facing widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
New emerging markets were also impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening boosted both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies faced capital flight and the appreciation of dollar-denominated debt values.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has caused volatility.
The U.S. re-imposed sanctions on Iran, pushing up oil prices. Subsequently, the U.S. government cancelled exemptions and threatened Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, resulting in a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of U.S. energy companies couldn't withstand it.
In addition, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worst of all, it's now clear that the benefits of last year's tax cuts have largely flowed into the corporate sector, rather than taking the form of higher real wages (adjusted for inflation) to households.
This suggests that household consumption may slow down soon and further affect the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline of the US and global stock markets is Trump's words and actions.
Worse than the risk of an outbreak of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "ceasefire" agreement with Chinese President Xi Jinping ) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve.
Due to these early criticisms, the market became a "scared rabbit" when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, hinting that it would raise interest rates more slowly in 2019.
It is more likely that the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance is a response to Trump's criticism of it.
Confronted with a hostile tweet from President Trump, Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to allocate funds for Trump's useless Mexico border wall, Trump decided to let the federal government shut down partially.
This move led the market into a state of panic, and as the government shut down, there were soon reports that Trump wanted to fire Powell – a move that could make the market correction evolve into a crash.
On the eve of Christmas, US Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell, and that the US fiscal situation was good – but this only highlighted the question of whether the situation was really good or not.
While it may not affect economic decision-making, recent government personnel changes also worry the market.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave their positions, leaving Trump's cabinet without a rational person.
The remaining ones will be all economic nationalists and hawkish diplomats, bowing only to Trump.
The possibility of all-around cold war against China cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War is extremely likely to lead to de-globalization and destroy global supply chains, but the technology industry will be the first to be hit, with the recent cases of ZTE and Huawei being clear evidence.
At the same time, Trump seems to be determined to break down the cohesion of the EU and NATO at a time when Europe is economically and politically unstable.
Especially, the investigation by Special Counsel Robert Mueller into Trump's relationship with Russia in the 2016 election is the sword of Damocles hanging over Trump's presidential career.
Trump is now the financial market's Rube Goldberg.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in an economic destruction from which he cannot extricate himself.
Today, the market sees this danger, and the risk of a financial crisis and global recession is rising.
